summary.seg: This manuscript contains Origen's Philocalia. Origen, a theologian who lived between the end of the 3rd and the first half of the 4th century CE, was reportedly a very prolific author; however, few of his writings survive, due to the condemnation of his teachings. The Philocalia is an anthology of texts by Origen in twenty-seven chapters, principally in the area of Biblical exegesis. The text, as it is common in the manuscripts, is preceded by a letter by Gregory of Nazianzus to Theodore bishop of Tyane, the most ancient document citing the Philocalia (see, among others, M. Harl, N. De Lange, Origène Philocalie, 1-20 Sur les Écritures et la lettre à Africanus sur l'histoire de Suzanne (Paris, 1983), pp. 19-24).

This copy of the Philocalia was produced at the beginning of the 17th century: the transcription of the Greek text was completed in September 1606, that of the Latin text in September 1604. The Greek text was copied from Munich, Bayerische Staatsbibliothek, Cod. Graec. 523 (see J. Armitage Robinson, 'On the Text of the Philocalia of Origen', The Journal of Philology 18 (1889), 36-68 (p. 47)). It was owned by the German librarian, editor and scholar David Hoeschel (1556-1617), and, later, by Thomas Gale.

Five folded leaves have been bound with the manuscript. These contain Origen's Epistula ad Iulium Africanum, and Sextus Iulius Africanus' Epistula ad Origenem. They were copied in 1629 by Patrick Young (1584-1652), Greek scholar and royal librarian.

support.material:
Western paper, folded in quarto. Watermarks: ff. iii-vii, 1:1-1:7, 2:1-2:51 Eagle, double-headed ( ca. 75 60 ), in the gutter, comparable to Briquet Aigle 300 , which is dated in 1591-1592.
ff. 2:52-2:[294a] Undefined form in a circle.
ff. [d], i-ii, [viii]-[x] Letter P/Y (?) surmounted by a shield with a cross ( 45 13 ), in the gutter, no parallels found in the main repertoires.
ff. [a]-[c], [e]-[g] Pro Patria, with a countermark formed by a coat of arms with letters G R in a circle ( 110 95 ), in the gutter, comparable to Heawood Pro Patria 3700 , which is dated to 1747 (England).

foliation.p: Foliation in brown ink, in Arabic numerals, in the upper margin right, from 1 to 294; modern foliation in pencil, in Roman numerals, in the upper margin right, from i to vii, for seven initial endleaves ([iia] is a stub); modern foliation in pencil, in Arabic numerals, in the upper margin right, from 1 to 5, for 5 single paper leaves, of larger dimension, folded and bound at the end of the manuscript between ff. [x] and [e]; at the beginning there are three unnumbered later endleaves (ff. [a]-[c]), and an unnumbered endleaf (f. [d]); at the end there are an unnumbered endleaf (f. [294a]), which is still attached to f. 294 along the upper edge (not cut, only 294r and [294a] verso are imaged), three unnumbered endleaves (ff. [viii]-[x]) and three unnumbered later endleaves (ff. [e]-[g]): [a]-[d] + i-ii, [iia], iii-vii + 1:1-1:7, 2:1-2:294, [294a] + [viii]-[x] + 3:1-3:5 + [e]-[g].

collation.p: The manuscript consists of quaternions and binions. Quire 9 is a quanternion which lacks the last leaf (a stub is visible, without loss of text). Folios 3:1-3:5 are single leaves, independent from the rest of the manuscript, which have been bound in it.

list.item: 5 leaves bound in the manuscript ff. 3:1-3:5

collation.catchwords: Horizontal catchwords in the lower part, right, of each page, in the scribe's hand.

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript is in fair condition. The book block is split between ff. 2:51-2:52. There are worm holes throughout, as well as orange and brown stains.

layoutDesc.layout: A single column of 16-19 lines, mostly 17. ca. 160 ca. 115

handNote.p: ff. 2:1r-2:294r Hand A: the text has been written by a single scribe, in a minuscule script, slanting to the right, probably by a non-Greek native scribe. Since in the Latin script are detectable forms which are similar to some of the Greek script (for example, the forms of a and alfa, of q and rho with a very inclined upright), the same scribe could have copied both the Greek and the Latin text.
The text is written in brown ink.
The scribe wrote also marginal notes throughout the whole text.
Hand a: another hand, also datable in the 17th century, wrote some notes on f. [d] recto; in the opinion of James (1902, p. 9), this could be the hand of Thomas Gale.
Hand b: another hand, also datable in the 17th century, wrote on f. iii recto, and added a text on f. 1:7r.

ff. [d] verso, 3:1r-3:5v Hand c: Patrick Young (1584-1652) Young, Patrick, 1584-1652 (for the identification see James (1902), p. 9), wrote some notes on f. [d] verso, and the texts on 5 folded leaves which were added to the manuscript (see Accompanying Material). He also added a text in Latin on f. 1:7r.

additions.p: On the left pastedown are written in brown ink, the old shelfmark E.16, the old number no 253, and the present shelfmark O.1.10.

On f. [d] recto there are some notes in Latin mentioning the edition of Origen Contra Celsum by David Hoeschel (the editio princeps, of 1606, printed in Augsburg), and the fact that the manuscript was collated with a codex of New College Library, Oxford (probably Oxford, New College, 147). Below are written two previous shelfmarks, E.16, and O.2.18, both erased.

On f. [d] verso there is a note in Latin, in Patrick Young's hand, mentioning the beginning of Theodoret's Quaestiones In Reges et Paralipomenon, as contained in a manuscript in Bibliotheca Christianissimi Regis, in the Library of the King of France.

On f. iii recto there is a sort of title page indicating:
the contents of the manuscript, Origenes Philocalia
the fact that it was copied from a manuscript from Cyprus by a scribe who knew Greek
that the Greek text is accompanied by the Latin translation by G. Genebrard
a dedication note from David Hoeschel to Henry Wotton, qualified as ambassador in Venice of the King of Britain (he was appointed in December 1603, and was in Venice since 1604; he was ambassador in the city also in 1616 and 1621).

On f. [x] verso there are two notes in Latin: the first cites Cicero's oration De provinciis consularibus, the second names Isaac Vossius in relation with the Philocalia: Philocaliam habet Isaacus Vossius bis.

binding.p:
Western modern binding. Paper cover over pasteboards; parchment on spine, on which are pasted three paper labels with the shelfmark, O 1 10. Edges painted in green; the colour on the fore-edge has faded partially, probably due to water or humidity.
210 160 ca. 65
binding.condition: The cover is a little discolored and worn near the edges. The spine is damaged.

accMat.p: Five folded leaves, ff. 3:1-3:5, have been bound between ff. [x]-[e].

They contain:
ff. 3:1r-3:5r
Origen Origen , Epistula ad Iulium Africanum, inc. Ωριγένης Ἀφρικἀνῳ ἀγαπήτῳ ἀδελφῷ ἐν θεῷ πατρὶ διὰ Ἰησοῦ Χριστοῦ τοῦ ἁγίου παιδὸς, εὖ πράττειν. Ἡ μὲν σὴ ἐπιστολή, expl. σὺ τὸν καλὸν ἡμῖν πάπαν Ἀπολινάριον ἄσπασαι, καὶ τοὺς ἀγαπῶντας ἡμᾶς (TLG 2042.045; CPG 1494; PG 11, 48-85)
f. 3:5r Colophon: Novembris 4to 1629 in palatio Divi Jacobi
ff. 3:5v
Sextus Iulius Africanus Iulius Africanus, Sextus 160-240 , Epistula ad Origenem, inc. Αφρικανοῦ περὶ τῆς κατὰ Σουσάνναν ἱστορίας. Χαῖρε κύριέ μου, expl. κατὰ νοῦν, θεῷ εὔχομαι (TLG 2956.003; CPG 1692; PG 11, 41-48)
The texts were copied by Patrick Young (see Hands) in 1629 in St James Palace.

origin.p: The copying of the Greek text was completed on 4th September 1606, whereas the transcription of the Latin translation was finished earlier, on 5th September 1604, as recorded by the two colophons written by the scribe on ff. 2:293v and 2:294r respectively. The text of the Philocalia was copied from a Cypriot manuscript, according to a note written on f. iii recto: Ex codice Cyprio descripta manu Graecae linguae studiosi, posita e regione Gilberti Genebrardi Interpretatione.

history.provenance:
The manuscript was probably in the hands of David Hoeschel (1556-1617) Hoeschel, David, 1556-1617 : on f. iii recto there is a dedication by him to
Henry Wotton (1568-1639) Wotton, Henry, Sir, 1568-1639 : Illustrissimo et generosissimo Domino Henrico Vuottonio, serenissimi et potentissimi Regis magnae Britanniae apud Vene- tos Oratori, felicem ex Italia in Germaniam gratulatus reditum David Hoeschelius, A.

The manuscript was part of the collection of the antiquary
Thomas Gale (ca. 1635-1702) Gale, Thomas, 1635?-1702 . It appears among Thomas Gale's Greek manuscripts in E. Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ, Oxoniæ 1697, p. 187: no. 5909 (75) Origenis Philocalia, una cum Genebrardi versione Latina, collata cum aliis MSS. et quidem editis melior. Fuit pridem liber Hoeschelii.; and p. 188: no. 5962 (128) Origenis et Jul. Africani Epistolae integrae de Susanna.
history.acquisition:
It was donated to the Library by Roger Gale (1672-1744) Gale, Roger, 1672-1744
in 1738. On f. [d] verso is pasted the Trinity College bookplate. Stamps of Trinity College Library on ff. 1:1r, 3:5v.
